Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 37th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
No big intro this week =E2=80=94 but one favor to ask: if you enjoy reading=
 The Weekly Dose of Optimism, the best way to support is to share us with a=
 friend. The Weekly Dose of Optimism is weekly publication that highlights =
five stories that make us more optimistic about the world. We celebrate hum=
ans and the great things we have and will achieve.=20
Now, let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Composer [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/14738e4f-d244-409f-9bc3-8be2282b9b16?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
You know Composer. I love Composer =E2=80=94 the investing app that helps y=
ou achieve superior returns with logic and data. Since founding its algorit=
hmic trading platform in 2020, Composer has helped over 20,000 customers tr=
ade 100s of millions of dollars. I=E2=80=99m one of them =E2=80=94 my Compo=
ser portfolio is actually up since I started using it last year, which is i=
ncredible because the portfolio of individual stocks I own is =E2=80=A6 not=
=2E
And Composer [ https://substack.com/redirect/14738e4f-d244-409f-9bc3-8be228=
2b9b16?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 is now integrated with ChatGPT-4, to help you better understand your inves=
ting Symphonies. Just copy+paste your Composer Symphony into ChatGPT-4, and=
 get a full breakdown of the strategy and the ability to ask additional que=
stions. Not sure where to start? Here are a few of our favorite prompts:
What are the risks of this strategy?=20
What should I add to diversify this strategy?=20
What type of strategy would be a good complement to this one?
Composer [ https://substack.com/redirect/14738e4f-d244-409f-9bc3-8be2282b9b=
16?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] was=
 already the smart way to invest, and with its ChatGPT-4 integration, it ju=
st got a lot smarter. Check it out for yourself, and as a Not Boring reader=
, you can get an extra free week of Composer=E2=80=99s trial offering by en=
tering =E2=80=9CNot Boring=E2=80=9D in the =E2=80=9CWhere did you hear abou=
t us?=E2=80=9D section. This exclusive offer lasts until Friday 4/14 at 11:=
59pm EST, so check out Composer now:
(1) Quantum Computers, explained with MKBHD [ http://Quantum Computers, exp=
lained with MKBHD ]
From Huge If True [ https://substack.com/redirect/cac99c90-321e-459b-af31-1=
8f6336264f8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]
We=E2=80=99re big fans of Cleo Abram=E2=80=99s Youtube series =E2=80=9CHuge=
 If True=E2=80=9D in which she explains important, often complicated topics=
 in simple language and with some dope video editing. The combo of the the =
two means that even guys like us can start to understand topics as complex =
as quantum computing.
In the WDoO #31, we covered that a team of Google researchers had achieved =
the second of six milestones on the way towards producing a =E2=80=9Cuseful=
 quantum computer.=E2=80=9D Quantum computing may be closer than we think, =
and the ways in which it could transform the world are hard to imagine beca=
use these are not simply bigger, faster computers=E2=80=A6they=E2=80=99re s=
omething different. They are 158 million times faster than the most powerfu=
l supercomputers we have today.
Cleo was joined by big-time tech YouTuber, Marques Brownlee, to take on the=
 topic. If you have 18 minutes to spare this weekend and want to get smarte=
r on what will be a very relevant topic in the future, we recommend watchin=
g!
(2) Checks and balances: Machine learning and zero-knowledge proofs [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/2a618f64-a554-4f5a-9dda-911512c2dbe8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]  [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/2a618f64-a554-4f5a-9dd=
a-911512c2dbe8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Elena Burger [ https://substack.com/redirect/75484828-6db9-4729-b8de-423db8=
b7ea40?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for a16z
The question isn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cwill AI be tremendously valuable,=E2=80=
=9D the question is =E2=80=9Chow do we build these systems in such a way th=
at anyone interacting with them will be able to reap its economic benefits =
and, if they so desire, ensure that their data is used in a way that honors=
 their right to privacy.=E2=80=9D
Packy here. Something that I feel very strongly about but have only started=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/71c149ef-d092-424f-a96e-e966377a6b69?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to put into=
 words is the idea that AI and crypto were made for each other, different t=
echnologies that came to be at right about the same time through a mix of r=
iding similar waves and that everything happens for a reason je ne sais quo=
i.=20
Venkatesh Rao captured the idea best in one of my favorite essays of the pa=
st few months, The Rise of Mediocre Computing [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/c8cbd707-ad1a-4c93-b2c3-3f503a242ca3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
It feels like AI and crypto are mathematical evil twins of sorts; that each=
 is somehow deeply incomplete without the other. The mild culture-warring b=
etween the two tribes is in fact a symptom of deeper kinships.
The hints are subtle and all over the place. I=E2=80=99ll take an inventory=
 in a future post, but here=E2=80=99s one as a sample: AIs can be used to g=
enerate =E2=80=9Cdeep fakes=E2=80=9D while cryptographic techniques can be =
used to reliably authenticate things against such fakery. Flipping it aroun=
d, crypto is a target-rich environment for scammers and hackers, and machin=
e learning can be used to audit crypto code for vulnerabilities. I am convi=
nced there is something deeper going on here. This reeks of real yin-yanger=
y that extends to the roots of computing somehow. It=E2=80=99s not just me =
hallucinating patterns where there are none.
Unifying AI and crypto at a foundational level smells like a problem on par=
 with unifying relativity and quantum mechanics in physics.
Elena=E2=80=99s essay focuses on one of the more immediately compelling int=
ersections of the two domains: ML and ZKPs. She adds more meat to the bone =
than VGR or I did.=20
The question, she writes, isn=E2=80=99t whether AI will be valuable =E2=80=
=94 of course it will be =E2=80=94 but how to best distribute that value an=
d allow people to control their own data. The answer Elena proposes isn=E2=
=80=99t to halt progress, but to =E2=80=9Cpush for models that are open-sou=
rce, and in cases where model providers want their weights or data to be pr=
ivate, to secure them with privacy-preserving zero-knowledge proofs that ar=
e on-chain and fully auditable.=E2=80=9D=20
The whole piece is worth reading =E2=80=94 Elena goes in-depth on five ways=
 ZKPs can be applied to ML and on shortcomings that remain to be overcome =
=E2=80=94 but there=E2=80=99s one point I want double-highlight:
High demand for blockchain compute has incentivized zero-knowledge proof re=
search.
As we=E2=80=99ve covered here [ https://substack.com/redirect/7a06fcd8-263a=
-40fc-93af-919a850b4357?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] before [ https://substack.com/redirect/14323764-dec7-49e5=
-8b8f-ac2fb6210bd3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], ZKPs are going to be useful beyond crypto, but research on th=
em has only accelerated so quickly because of crypto. It=E2=80=99s pretty i=
ncredible how these things line up.=20
(3) Artificial intelligence has advanced despite having few resources dedic=
ated to its development =E2=80=93 now investments have increased substantia=
lly [ https://substack.com/redirect/3d4605a1-63ee-4a60-b34e-55e3bcc009aa?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Max Roser [ https://substack.com/redirect/4a608ec4-c81d-45f7-92c6-dc6d7f90b=
46a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] fo=
r Our World in Data
The developments in the past happened despite the fact that funding and bra=
inpower dedicated to AI were quite limited. As these charts have shown, thi=
s has changed. Across a range of metrics, the resources dedicated to AI dev=
elopment have increased substantially.
The fact that the field advanced with relatively small resources, and now h=
as much larger resources at its disposal =E2=80=93 leading to rapid advance=
s [ https://substack.com/redirect/3061d8cf-6df0-4ef2-be91-6ff1639d1d40?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in the las=
t few years =E2=80=93 is one reason why I expect AI technology to continue =
to develop rapidly and to exert a larger and larger influence on our world.=
=C2=A0
ChatGPT and other Transformer-based models have captured the world=E2=80=99=
s attention, but AI advancements may just be heating up. Why? The corporate=
 investment in AI has gone exponential in the last three years, with no sig=
ns of slowing down.
In the three years prior to the publication of =E2=80=9CAttention Is All Yo=
u Need [ https://substack.com/redirect/46fcebc2-bc7f-44dd-9efa-6318b047a4f5=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94 the 2017 research paper from Google that introduced Transform=
ers =E2=80=94 about $75B was invested in AI globally. In 2021 alone, that n=
umber more than doubled to $160B. And with the recent GPT-hype, I=E2=80=99d=
 be willing to bet 2023 will be closer to $300B. That=E2=80=99s a >10x incr=
ease in annual investment over the last decade.
If we think things are crazy now, imagine what $300B+ of annual AI R&D and =
a useful quantum computer will yield=E2=80=A6
Back in the present day, you can=E2=80=99t check Twitter without getting hi=
t with at least 2-3 very cool AI products/advancements each day, spun up by=
 individuals without funding. Here are two that caught our eye:
GPT-4 Coding Assistant [ https://substack.com/redirect/2b39d0b1-4bfd-4748-a=
3fd-b4352451b48b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ]
Task-driven autonomous agent [ https://substack.com/redirect/bf488487-4c38-=
4ded-93ef-9b85fda4bcc6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
(Twitter has seemingly restricted embedded Tweets in Substack =E2=80=94 tha=
nks Elon!)
(4) UK develops genetic early warning system for future pandemics [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/f1c602f5-6621-404e-9c4f-4f6be58b8eb7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Robin McKie [ https://substack.com/redirect/364eb630-9897-4a1c-8e23-bcc6b3b=
905dc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for The Guardian
The ultimate aim of the project =E2=80=93 the Respiratory Virus and Microbi=
ome Initiative [ https://substack.com/redirect/5ea49071-6621-4c7b-9b70-438c=
366640e0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] =E2=80=93 is to create a system that would deploy DNA sequencing technol=
ogy to identify all viral, bacterial and fungal species in a single sample =
collected from a nose swab from a patient.
Remember back in 2020/2021 when new variants of Covid were popping up in sp=
ecific geographies and we were able to pinpoint the severity and the infect=
iousness of those variants? That information, and our ability to access it =
quickly, was the result of genomic sequencing technology and it played a vi=
tal role in containing the threat of the pandemic.
Now that same technology is being targeted at other viruses including influ=
enza, RSV, and other coronaviruses to help us better surveil, track, and ul=
timately fight the viruses. The technology, which was developed in the UK a=
nd only accessible to a few other developed countries, is now going global.
We don=E2=80=99t know when or where the next pandemic will start, but this =
time, thanks to a surveillance network of more affordable and advanced tech=
nologies, we may be more prepared to take it on.=20
(5) Rex Woodbury on Optimism [ https://substack.com/redirect/b2ecdb38-633e-=
4474-abe2-17f2fea7d84f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Rex Woodbury [ https://substack.com/redirect/d94bab78-6abd-4515-a2f7-f=
70f18747578?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]
Index Partner and author of the Substack Digital Native [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/06921c70-dc96-43b9-9dad-35fb4b5739de?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] Rex Woodbury dropped a worthwhi=
le =F0=9F=A7=B5 (link to tweet [ https://substack.com/redirect/b2ecdb38-633=
e-4474-abe2-17f2fea7d84f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]) on how capitalism and technology are drivers of positiv=
e social impact at scale. He gives reason to be optimistic on topics rangin=
g from climate, biotech, work, and even dating. Life has certainly gotten b=
etter over the past 200 years [ https://substack.com/redirect/c649b18c-8ae5=
-4db6-b488-fcc3dd23d559?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and that has almost certainly be the result of accelerat=
ing technological advancements.
There=E2=80=99s a lot of pessimism out there, but we agree with Rex that th=
e good outweighs the bad and we thank him for the healthy dose of optimismp=
orn.=20
And now, to those of you who celebrate:
Did you enjoy reading this Weekly Dose of Optimism?
Yes [ https://substack.com/redirect/1503846b-21c9-4b0f-bd81-1aeb887c52c5?j=
